<paragraph blockId="54.[264,1323,1039,1225]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">
Ancestral areas were calculated for five major clades mapped on one of the 779 MP trees (
<figureCitation box="[273,364,1079,1105]" captionStart="FIGURE 114" captionStartId="55.[264,367,1243,1267]" captionTargetBox="[457,1126,336,1205]" captionTargetId="figure-232@55.[449,1138,329,1216]" captionTargetPageId="55" captionText="FIGURE 114. One of 779 shortest trees showing ancestral areas for five clades, B = central US and Canada, D = southwestern US and Mexico, E = Central America, F = western South America. Red = species originally placed in Holomelina, Blue = species placed in Virbia, Black = outgroups." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5058302" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5058302/files/figure.png" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Fig.114</figureCitation>
) using Hausdorf’s method (
<bibRefCitation author="Hausdorf, B." box="[693,875,1079,1105]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" pagination="445 - 456" refId="ref21697" refString="Hausdorf, B. (1998) Weighted ancestral area analysis and solution of the redundant distribution problem. Systematic Biology, 47, 445 - 456." type="journal article" year="1998">Hausdorf 1998</bibRefCitation>
). These clades are present in the strict consensus tree (
<figureCitation box="[454,526,1119,1145]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="16.[264,368,1787,1811]" captionTargetBox="[300,1296,418,1734]" captionTargetId="figure-81@16.[287,1332,393,1764]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 7. Strict consensus of 123 trees L = 1356, CI = 0.47, RI = 0.65 resulting from the analysis of male­female pairs MF. Parallel lines = species placed in Holomelina, Solid lines = species placed in Virbia, Broken lines = outgroups.." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5058200" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5058200/files/figure.png" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
) and have a Bremer support of at least 3. Individual gain and loss scores are given for each clade for each area as well as the resulting Weighted Area Index (= WAI; 
<tableCitation box="[368,458,1199,1225]" captionStart="TABLE 4" captionStartId="54.[264,352,1278,1302]" captionText="TABLE 4. Weighted area indices. Clade numbers refer to Figure 114 and areas A­H refer to Figure 104 and text. G = Gain, L = Loss, WAI = Weighted Area Index." pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Table 4</tableCitation>
).
</paragraph>
